observations.recommendation:
We recommended that:

The Municipal Accounting Office draw the necessary adjusting entries to appropriately recognize the advance payments of Real Property Tax collections for CY 2023 collected in CY 2022 amounting to P1,624,120.43;




Henceforth, the Municipal Treasury Office shall prepare and submit in a separate report all advance receipts of taxes from taxpayers to the Municipal Accounting Office to facilitate proper accounting thereof in accordance with IPSAS 23 and COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that the LCE:

Require all concerned officers and employees to ensure that every Disbursement Voucher, Purchase Request, Purchase Order, Request for Quotations and Inspection and Acceptance Report are numbered sequentially, dated and that all necessary information in the documents are properly accomplished to give worthy credence as valid supporting documents as follows:

- ensure that the details in the supporting documents relating to claims of travelling expenses are always complete; 
- require the supplier to put his name or indicate his authority and sign in the Purchase Order in order to bind him with the contract;
- require the drivers to ensure that the details in the Driver’s Trip Tickets are always complete; 
- the Municipal Treasurer must always stamp “Paid” upon the face of the     vouchers and on all its supporting documents upon payment of the claims; and

We recommended that the LCE:
Require all concerned officers and employees to ensure that every Disbursement Voucher, Purchase Request, Purchase Order, Request for Quotations and Inspection and Acceptance Report are numbered sequentially, dated and that all necessary information in the documents are to be properly accomplished to give worthy credence as valid supporting documents;

Require all concerned officers and employees to ensure that the details in the supporting documents relating to claims of travelling expenses are always complete; 

Require all concerned officers and employees to require the supplier to put his name or indicate his authority and sign in the Purchase Order in order to bind him with the contract;

Require the drivers to ensure that the details in the Driver’s Trip Tickets are always complete; 

Require the Municipal Treasurer to always stamp “Paid” upon the face of the vouchers and on all its supporting documents upon payment of the claims; and

Ensure that sound system of internal control is being installed, implemented and monitored in the Municipality in compliance with Section 124 of PD 1445.

We recommended that:
the Local Chief Executive ensure that sound internal controls are established in the management of cash, cash items and accountable forms;
partitions and safety deposit boxes/locked drawers be provided to the Collecting Officers to protect the money and the accountable forms from risks of loss and misuse;
the Municipal Treasurer maintain a copy of the RIS and permanent record books for accountable forms for easy monitoring of the receipt, issuance and its whereabouts;
the liquidating officer and all collectors maintain individual cashbook to record their daily collections as prescribed by existing regulations. The use of the cashbook will facilitate monitoring of their respective accountabilities as of a given date; and
the Municipal Treasurer record transactions daily or immediately upon their occurrence and to regularly update his cashbook and certify the same monthly pursuant to provisions of the Manual on the New Government Accounting System for LGUs, to facilitate the determination of his cash accountabilities.

We reiterated our prior year’s recommendations that the LCE:
Require all concerned officers and employees to ensure that every Disbursement Voucher, Purchase Request, Purchase Order, Request for Quotations and Inspection and Acceptance Report are numbered sequentially, dated and that all necessary information in the documents are properly accomplished to give worthy credence as valid supporting documents as follows;
ensure that the details in the supporting documents relating to claims of travelling expenses are always complete;
require the supplier to put his name or indicate his authority and sign in the Purchase Order in order to bind him with the contract;
require the drivers to ensure that the details in the Driver’s Trip Tickets are always complete;
the Municipal Treasurer must always stamp “Paid” upon the face of the     vouchers and on all its supporting documents upon payment of the claims; and
Ensure that sound system of internal control in the disbursement of funds is being installed, implemented and monitored in the Municipality in compliance with Section 124 of PD No. 1445 to prevent the payment of illegal, irregular or unlawful transactions.

We recommended that the Management:

Undertake the one-time cleansing of the Property, Plant and Equipment in accordance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO to maintain the required Property, Plant and Equipment Ledger Cards, Real Property Ledger Cards and Property Cards, respectively;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO to prepare and submit the Inventory Reports using the prescribed Reports on the Physical Count of PPEs and reconcile the deficiencies noted in the records maintained by the Municipal Accountant and Municipal GSO and effect the necessary actions;

Require the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal GSO to ensure that all PPE items covered with Property Acknowledgment Receipt are included in the Reports on the Physical Count of PPEs and Inventory Reports of the Accounting Office. Likewise, require the Municipal GSO to use Property Acknowledgment Receipt in issuing the property to end-users, and ensure that PARs are renewed every January of the third year after issue; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the reclassification of the misclassified accounts to fairly present the financial statements; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the correcting entry for the unrecognized Medical Equipment amounting to P685,000.00; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to disclose all required financial information in the Notes to Financial Statements to assist the users in understanding the financial statements and to provide them with additional information value.

We recommended that the Management:

Strictly observe the provisions of Section 4(1) of PD 1445 and Section 305(a) of RA No. 7160 and ensure that all disbursements are supported by an appropriation;

Require the Municipal Budget Officer and Municipal Accountant to maintain the required registries to prevent incurrence of expenditures in excess of allotments;

Ensure that the municipal annual budget be carefully prepared and reviewed so that the actual needs of the Municipality are properly allocated in the budget;

Ensure that the Obligation Request, which is the basis for recording of obligations in the registries, be properly accomplished to facilitate monitoring of expenses and balances of appropriations; and

Submit a written explanation and Municipal Resolutions for Realignment/ Augmentation, if any, for the incurrence of illegal expenditures, otherwise, the full amount shall be disallowed in audit since the same is considered as an illegal disbursement of public funds.

We recommended that the Management: 
adopt an austere policy on the payment of representation and miscellaneous expenses, which is consistent with the provisions of law and COA rules and regulations; 

ensure that payments for meals and snacks are actually incurred in the conduct of official business, reception, or entertainment;

require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all disbursements be supported with complete documentary evidence in compliance with Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445; and 

refund the amount of P154,233.50 disallowed in audit since the same is considered as irregular disbursement of public funds.

We recommended that the Management: 
set a policy on the grant of communication expense identifying the allowed officials and employees, the amount to be granted and the plan to be used in order to identify the most favorable option for the Municipality’s scarce resources;

refrain from granting communication allowance to individuals not qualified to receive the same; 

require Mr. Gunnacao and the contractual employees to refund the amounts they received as communication allowance;

require the Municipal Accountant to effect correcting entries for the error committed in recording liquidation of cash advance for the month of August 2020; and 

require the concerned officers and employees to submit the noted lacking documents for the payment of communication expenses and ensuing claims for such expenses.

